refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
callablefun stringfunction_name
fun takes a constant string and returns a callable representing the function named by the constant string. In the typechecker, the return value of this function has a proper function type, based upon looking up the function prototype named in the argument. This allows the typechecker to properly check callbacks which may be passed around; traditional PHP passes around strings, which are impossible to statically analyze and check invocations of.

&reftitle.parameters;




   function_name



     Function of which to return a typecheckable callable form. Must be a constant, single-quoted string.

  &reftitle.examples;



    fun gives the typechecker visibility into a callback and function call


<?hh

function f(string $s): void {}

function test(): void {
  // The typechecker cannot determine what function $f refers to. It will reject
  // this in strict mode; partial mode will reject it, but with an error that may
  // not be as helpful (see first type checker error below). This fails at runtime.
  $f = 'f';
  $f(1);

  // But, with a call to fun(), we can know what function $f refers to, and
  // check its arguments statically. This will produce a more valuable type
  // error (as shown in the second type checker error below).
  $f = fun('f');
  $f(1);
}



 The non fun() usage will be type checked as follows


f.php:11:3,7: This call is invalid, this is not a function, it is a string



 The fun() usage will be type checked as follows


f.php:17:6,6: Invalid argument
  f.php:3:13,18: This is a string
  f.php:17:6,6: It is incompatible with an int







    fun is most useful for callbacks


<?hh

function run_callback((function(string): void) $f, string $s): void {
  $f($s);
}

function test2(): void {
  // Although this works at runtime, the typechecker will reject this, since 'f'
  // is a string, not a function.
  run_callback('f', 'test');

  // But this is acceptable:
  run_callback(fun('f'), 'test');
}
